=javascript>PNGGIF("images/fadetowhite", 75, 16, "", "");</script><noscript><img src="images/fadetowhite.gif" width=75 height=16 alt=""></noscript></td><td class=LanguageBarRight nowrap><a href="languages.html">Supports <b>19</b> Languages</a></td></tr></table><div class=Topic><p class=FirstParagraph>Natural Docs is an open-source documentation generator for <a href="languages.html">multiple programming languages</a>.&nbsp; You document your code in a <a href="documenting.html">natural syntax</a> that reads like plain English.&nbsp; Natural Docs then scans your code and builds high-quality <a href="documentation/html/">HTML documentation</a> from it.</p></div></div><div class=Topic><div class=TopicTitle>Current Version</div><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 class=VersionTable><tr><td class=Version><a href="download.html">1.5</a></td><td rowspan=2 class=VersionDescription><p>Natural Docs is stable and ready to be used in real world projects.&nbsp; Make sure to <a href="languages.html">check the level of support</a> your language has to see if Natural Docs will document all of your code automatically or just what you write for it.</p></td></tr><tr><td class=VersionDownload><a href="download.html">Download</a></td></tr></table></div><div class=NewsBox><div class=TopicTitle id=SubscribeTopicTitle>News</div><div class=Subscribe><a href="mailinglist.html">Get notified of new releases via e-mail</a>&nbsp; &middot;&nbsp; <a href="feeds/news.xml">Subscribe to the news feed</a></div><div class=NewsItem><div class=NewsTitle>Natural Docs 1.5 released</div><div class=NewsDate>July 22nd, 2010</div><p>Hey look at that, I&rsquo;m not dead... again!&nbsp; First the features, then an update on the project.</p><p>The biggest new feature is the addition of syntax highlighting.&nbsp; Both prototypes and <code>(start code)</code> segments will be highlighted via the integration of <a href="http://code.google.com/p/google-code-prettify/">Google Prettify</a>.&nbsp; You can turn this off or extend it to <code>&gt;</code>, <code>:</code>, and <code>|</code> prefixed lines with <a href="running.html">the <code>-hl</code> command line option</a>.</p><p>You can also use named links instead of just raw URLs and e-mail addresses.&nbsp; This is done with <a href="documenting/reference.html#Linking">the &ldquo;at&rdquo; keyword</a>, which was chosen because it often fits right into the sentence and leaves the source readable: &ldquo;Visit the &lt;web site at http://www.naturaldocs.org&gt;&rdquo; becomes &ldquo;Visit the <a href="http://www.naturaldocs.org">web site</a>&rdquo; in the output.</p><p>The licensing has been changed.&nbsp; Natural Docs has moved from version 2 of the GPL to version 3 of the AGPL.&nbsp; I was planning to do this with 2.0 and leave 1.x alone, but Prettify&rsquo;s Apache license wouldn&rsquo;t be compatible otherwise so 1.x gets it too.&nbsp; I&rsquo;ve also updated the license text in numerous files to make explicit what I thought was always assumed: any generated documentation you create is your own and not subject to the GPL.&nbsp; The JavaScript and CSS files bundled with it are still part of Natural Docs, but their licensing doesn&rsquo;t apply to the documentation as a whole.</p><p>A bunch of minor bugs are fixed as always, but I&rsquo;m not going to go through them except for one.&nbsp; Natural Docs will now handle files with classic Mac line breaks, which some IDEs apparently still use.&nbsp; This is more of a problem with Perl sucking than Natural Docs, but I&rsquo;ve successfully worked around it.&nbsp; Perl still chokes on UTF-16 files though.</p><p>So anyway, on to the project as a whole.&nbsp; I&rsquo;ve actually been sidetracked with a different project for the better part of the past year so no real progress has been made in that time.&nbsp; Now that that&rsquo;s come to a close I&rsquo;m ready to get back into it.&nbsp; I&rsquo;m still going to be dedicating most of my time to the C# version because all the old reasons still apply: the engine needs an overhaul and I can&rsquo;t imagine doing it in Perl.&nbsp; However, unlike before I&rsquo;m going to occasionally drop back into the Perl code instead of just letting it languish.&nbsp; If there&rsquo;s a feature that works into the existing architecture easily I&rsquo;ll add it, and I might backport a few from 2.0.</p><p>1.5 illustrates this well.&nbsp; Prettify was something that was fairly easy to tack on.&nbsp; A native highlighter would have been better but isn&rsquo;t worth the effort at this point.&nbsp; Named links were backported from 2.0 because they fit into the architecture easily.&nbsp; And Perl&rsquo;s inability to handle Unicode and cross-platform line breaks transparently is another example of why it&rsquo;s better to switch to something more modern.&nbsp; It wouldn&rsquo;t be a deal breaker on its own but I have many such examples.</p><p>So that&rsquo;s it for now.&nbsp; People occasionally ask me when 2.0&rsquo;s coming I don&rsquo;t have an answer.&nbsp; Time isn&rsquo;t as plentiful as is was years ago when I started Natural Docs and didn&rsquo;t have a real job yet.&nbsp; I&rsquo;ve been sneaking it in where I can, and actually having some time away from the work I&rsquo;ve already done has been good for me.&nbsp; While reacquainting myself with the code I got a fresh look at it and saw where it could be better.&nbsp; The continued evolution of Mono during that time means I can take advantage of newer language features.&nbsp; And the other project increased my knowledge of JavaScript considerably which bodes well for what I can do with the output in the future.</p><div class=NewsSig>- <a href="#" onClick="location.href='mai' + 'lto:' + 'gregv' + 'alure' + '@' + 'natural' + 'docs.org'; return false;">Greg</a></div></div><div class=NewsItem><div class=NewsTitle>Natural Docs 1.4 released</div><div class=NewsDate>May 8th, 2008</div><p>Natural Docs 1.4 is finally, finally here.&nbsp; There are no surprises if you&rsquo;ve been following the development releases, but let&rsquo;s go through the big new features for those who haven&rsquo;t.</p><p>First we have search support.&nbsp; If you look at the <a href="documentation/html/">documentation</a> there&rsquo;s an inconspicuous little search entry at the bottom of the menu.&nbsp; If you start typing in there it will pull up results from the index as you type.&nbsp; What&rsquo;s nice about it is that it&rsquo;s all done in DHTML so there&rsquo;s no special software to install.&nbsp; You can just upload your output directory to a web server or open it from your hard drive and it will work.&nbsp; Also, you don&rsquo;t have to do anything at all to add it to your documentation.&nbsp; Just run the new version of Natural Docs and it will appear.</p><p>Next is <a href="documenting/reference.html#JavadocCompatibility">Javadoc compatibility</a>.&nbsp; If you have <a href="languages.html">full language support</a>, Natural Docs will be able to read any existing Javadoc comments you&rsquo;ve written and incorporate them into the output.&nbsp; The conversion can sometimes be imperfect but it&rsquo;s better than rewriting them all by hand.&nbsp; As a bonus, you can also write Natural Docs comments without the topic line by using the Javadoc comment symbols but otherwise using Natural Docs&rsquo; formatting.</p><p>We also have <a href="documenting/reference.html#Images">image support</a> now.&nbsp; You can embed images in your documentation just by writing <code>(see image.jpg)</code> so it makes sense when you&rsquo;re reading it from the source code instead of looking like a HTML tag.&nbsp; You can tell Natural Docs where to look for images with the <code>-img</code> command line option.</p><p>The ActionScript parser has been updated for ActionScript 3, and the C# parser has been updated to include some of the 2.0 language features.&nbsp; You can now document structs in C++ as a single entry and all its members will appear in a prototype.&nbsp; You can still use the old method of documenting each member individually if you want.</p><p>As for minor tweaks, the Note and Notes keywords have been removed.&nbsp; These often caused Natural Docs to include comments that weren&rsquo;t meant for it in the output, so they&rsquo;re gone.&nbsp; You can add them back by <a href="customizingtopics.html#ChangingKeywords">editing <code>Topics.txt</code></a> if you need them.&nbsp; You can also add timestamps to the footer of your documentation by <a href="menu.html#Footers">editing <code>Menu.txt</code></a>.&nbsp; There&rsquo;s now an <code>-oft</code> (<code>--only-file-titles</code>) command line option that tells Natural Docs not to guess at what the title of a file should be by its contents and to only use the file name.&nbsp; The CSS structure of the generated output has changed a bit so <a href="documentation/html/files/Info/CSSGuide-txt.html#History">check the changelog</a> if you&rsquo;ve built your own custom style.&nbsp; There are too many bugs fixed to list.</p><p>The web site got a few updates as well, including <a href="documenting/walkthrough.html">a walkthrough</a> of the documentation syntax to help new people get started and a <a href="feeds/news.xml">RSS feed of the news</a>.</p><p>For those of you who didn&rsquo;t see the news on the web site, this is probably the last major release using the current Perl codebase.&nbsp; Natural Docs has needed a big overhaul for quite some time now.&nbsp; I&rsquo;ve had a number of features in the back of my mind that I just can&rsquo;t do under the current architecture.&nbsp; Ripping out the engine has always been planned but it&rsquo;s a big project and I wasn&rsquo;t always eager to work on it.</p><p>However, I&rsquo;m currently working on Natural Docs 2.0 which is just that.&nbsp; Since I would have needed to rebuild most of it anyway I&rsquo;m taking the opportunity to switch languages, and I settled on C#.&nbsp; Perl is great for what it is but I don&rsquo;t think it&rsquo;s up to what I had planned, and after working on it for a few months I think I made the right choice.</p><p>Natural Docs 2.0 will run with .NET on Windows and <a href="http://www.mono-project.com">Mono</a> on Linux and Mac OS X.&nbsp; It will <u>always</u> be cross-platform; if a feature of .NET doesn&rsquo;t work with Mono I won&rsquo;t use it.&nbsp; It will also incorporate <a href="http://www.sqlite.org">SQLite</a> which runs in all three places as well.&nbsp; I&rsquo;m keeping things close to the vest for now but I&rsquo;ll start putting out code and development releases as it gets usable.&nbsp; I may start a developer blog talking about why I chose these things and the upcoming features if there&rsquo;s any interest.&nbsp; <a href="#" onClick="location.href='mai' + 'lto:' + 'gregv' + 'alure' + '@' + 'natural' + 'docs.org'; return false;">Let me know though</a>, because I don&rsquo;t know if I&rsquo;ll bother if I&rsquo;m just going to be talking to myself, not that that&rsquo;s ever stopped anyone from blogging before.</p><p>So there you go.&nbsp; Shiny new 1.4 now, 2.0 in the works.</p><div class=NewsSig>- <a href="#" onClick="location.href='mai' + 'lto:' + 'gregv' + 'alure' + '@' + 'natural' + 'docs.org'; return false;">Greg</a></div></div><div class=NewsItem><div class=NewsTitle>Natural Docs 1.4 release candidate 3</div><div class=NewsDate>March 18th, 2008</div><p>Yet another release candidate.&nbsp; Mostly this fixes various language parsing issues:</p><ul><li>Allow generics in base classes in C#.</li><li>Allow angle brackets in function names in C# to support explicitly implementing generic interfaces.</li><li>Allow * as ActionScript function return type.</li><li>Fixed enum property parsing in Languages.txt, which fixes enum handling in C#, Java, JavaScript, VB, and Ruby.</li><li>Allow $, #, and _ before &ldquo;as&rdquo; or &ldquo;is&rdquo; in PL/SQL prototypes.</li><li>Allow _ before &ldquo;is&rdquo; in Ada prototypes.</li></ul><p>There&rsquo;s also a few minor changes such as being able to put * or _ immediately before or after links, such as <code>*&lt;link&gt;*</code>.&nbsp; &ldquo;operator&rdquo; and &ldquo;operators&rdquo; are now keywords for functions, and it won&rsquo;t stop with an error message if it can&rsquo;t open extensionless files, which is useful in case Natural Docs mistakenly tries to open a system file it shouldn&rsquo;t be looking at.</p><div class=NewsSig>- <a href="#" onClick="location.href='mai' + 'lto:' + 'gregv' + 'alure' + '@' + 'natural' + 'docs.org'; return false;">Greg</a></div></div><div class=OldNews><a href="news/">Older News...</a></div></div></td></tr><tr><td></td><td class=SideMenuBottom><table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td class=SideMenuBottomLeft><img src="images/menu/bottomleft.png" width=18 height=19></td><td class=SideMenuBottomRight><img src="images/menu/bottomright.png" width=18 height=19></td></tr></table></td><td class=BodyBottom>Copyright &copy; 2003-2010 Greg Valure</td></tr></table><script language=JavaScript><!--
